          "username": "p.ospaly"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-14 10:03:32.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: -Code-Review\n\nIt seems like we took the longer route to applicate my proposal and still we are not there yet. I fail to see what using subnet instead of ip brings - maybe it is the correct approach what solves some other issue but I am missing explanation. I see it again as a possible place for problem - you are filtering ips and what if user have multiple ips on that subnet and it filters out the ip he actually wants? I just really dont understand why we are not using the obvious option and go by the fishy route. I am removing my vote because this patchset basically does what I proposed but I am still unhappy that we are denying the user to pick exactly the ip he wants...",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "67a2aab9cc8959049d25a0bcf9a94fc3138828b7",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4886,
          "name": "Petr Ospalý",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "p.ospaly@email.cz",
          "username": "p.ospaly"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-14 12:16:15.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1 Verified-1\n\nI test the change now:\nfatal: [infrastructure-server]: FAILED! => {\"msg\": \"The ipaddr filter requires python-netaddr be installed on the ansible controller\"}",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "ef92056ed95ade1244f62a9fd354f9b8a61a30bb",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4886,
          "name": "Petr Ospalý",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "p.ospaly@email.cz",
          "username": "p.ospaly"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-14 15:19:02.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThis will fix that problem: add netaddr in the ansible/docker/Dockerfile just after the jmespath in the pip3 install command",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "db9afe966796a7ecbd0ab8b1a9ae0c1dcc6be07b",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5019,
          "name": "Michal Zegan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
          "username": "m.zegan"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-16 09:37:54.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nWell, generally a subnet should be enough. subnets really should not overlap and even in case you have more than one ip per subnet, it is still one interface. Generally we probably do not need to support every case possible including those that are rare, so subnet seems enough.\nBtw about adding netaddr, could you please add that as a followup commit?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "7e335fd53ac693d4574a600e46556d7114b91448",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 4886,
          "name": "Petr Ospalý",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "p.ospaly@email.cz",
          "username": "p.ospaly"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-16 09:54:38.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI can, I did not want to hijack your patchset - on the topic - there is a very common usage when you do use multiple ips on one interface and in one subnet - the floating ip - user can choose to have infra node as HA - that means on that same subnet he can have basic ip for the infra-node1 (not-floating) and another floating ip on the same subnet which is added/deleted when failover is done and which is migrating between two or more nodes (pacemaker, keepalived etc.). In this case the floating ip would be the one ansible should have configured - but probably it would not be selected due to this autoconfigure. I just dont understand why we are making this flaw here and what is the benefit to have subnet instead of explicit ip. It is not that I want to have this change exactly as I proposed if this solution is superior but I dont see any upside and I already point out usecase when it has big drawback.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "114206e9e4b6d0e398e8bf49b7ede1b7b4830c49",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5019,
          "name": "Michal Zegan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
          "username": "m.zegan"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-16 10:12:52.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nWell i meant a separate commit for adding netaddr, separate change. Not sure if it fits exactly to *this* change.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "80f2b62c99f068f125772c37b06738e9d55ac4d6",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5019,
          "name": "Michal Zegan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
          "username": "m.zegan"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-01-16 10:16:41.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> I can, I did not want to hijack your patchset - on the topic -\n > there is a very common usage when you do use multiple ips on one\n > interface and in one subnet - the floating ip - user can choose to\n > have infra node as HA - that means on that same subnet he can have\n > basic ip for the infra-node1 (not-floating) and another floating ip\n > on the same subnet which is added/deleted when failover is done and\n > which is migrating between two or more nodes (pacemaker, keepalived\n > etc.). In this case the floating ip would be the one ansible should\n > have configured - but probably it would not be selected due to this\n > autoconfigure. I just dont understand why we are making this flaw\n > here and what is the benefit to have subnet instead of explicit ip.\n > It is not that I want to have this change exactly as I proposed if\n > this solution is superior but I dont see any upside and I already\n > point out usecase when it has big drawback.\n\nI am not sure if we even support any kind of HA use case, my guess is that we do not. I would argue that that setup is currently not really possible here. So for all supported setups the current solution should work.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
